on fork blockage by proteins in vivo. This work led to a publication in Molecular Cell in 2009.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>Our initial work demonstrated the importance of specific helicases in maintaining replication fork movement along protein-bound DNA in vitro. This led to a molecular explanation of the ability of RNA polymerase mutations to restore viability to cells with defects in fork movement along protein-bound DNA.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2008-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>Our previous MRC-funded work had established an in vitro system for the reconstitution of replication fork movement and subsequent fork blockage. However, this previous system employed a 9 subunit complex that was only partially purified. During the course of this current MRC project grant we purified all subunits required for the reconstitution of DNA replication in vitro.</gtr:description><gtr:id>FBF3D04B-BDE1-4100-93D9-6C8D55F6676A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Having all the components of a replication machine available in a purified form proved critical for our recent study demonstrating that replication forks contain two types of motor, not one. Moreover, having such a defined system allowed us to demonstrate that these two replicative motors interact both physically and functionally at the fork.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>false</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>A defined system for in vitro analysis of DNA replication</gtr:title><gtr:type>Technology assay or reagent</gtr:type></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTec